<br>
Faervas and I returned to Kedge last night, with a single party of levels 51-54, 5 casters and a monk (read: no bashers <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   ).  When it came time to start pulling the swirlspines (very MR cleric seahorses that guard Phinney), none of the casters, save the 53 druid, was able to get *anything* to hit them, and cleric and chanter stuns were 100% ineffective, even with the mob tashed.  The first one CHed, and was still casting.  I loaded Mana Sieve, as ToT wouldn't stick either, nor would any of my debuffs (I was able to get one Strip Enchantment to successfully remove a damage shield, however).  I found that, over the course of the night, if I got seven or more sieves off on the mob, it would be unable to CH.  Any less (in other words, if the mob was beat down too *fast* for sufficient mana to have been drained from it! or I tried doing other things while the fight was going on) and it would invariably get off a CH.  So, in the absence of a dedicated siever (which is a tremendous drain of mana on a chanter, I might add), bashing is crucial to preventing these creatures from healing themselves or others, and they will CH multiple times if given the chance...<br>
<br>
As Faervas indicated in the original post, it would have been *nice* if some paladins would have been present to do this job (yay the oft-snubbed paladins!), but in their absense, some shield action from the warriors, especially since this was a planned raid, should have been planned for.<br>
<br>
Regards,<br>
Nydia Ywalmoriel<br>
